<div id="review_2610650569" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2610650569" />
    <a title="Deborah Ideiosepius" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4802663-deborah-ideiosepius"><img alt="Deborah Ideiosepius" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1425943228p2/4802663.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2610650569?book_show_action=true">Nov 29, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Deborah Ideiosepius" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Deborah Ideiosepius" href="/user/show/4802663-deborah-ideiosepius">Deborah Ideiosepius</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780553232059" href="/book/show/77309.Tea_with_the_Black_Dragon">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4802663-deborah-ideiosepius?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4802663-deborah-ideiosepius?shelf=classic-sci-fi">classic-sci-fi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4802663-deborah-ideiosepius?shelf=magic-realism">magic-realism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4802663-deborah-ideiosepius?shelf=2018-reading-challenge">2018-reading-challenge</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4802663-deborah-ideiosepius?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2610650569" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12088098526747436151">This is an absolute gem of a book!<br/><br/>Odd, unconventional and uniformly charming to read it is rather unique and, as such, it is not easily boxed into any category, I would say that &apos;Fantasy&apos;, &apos;Classic science fiction&apos;, or &apos;magic realism&apos; would all fit perfectly well.<br/><br/>Martha Macnamara flies into town at the invitation of the daughter she has not seen for years. Liz is a computer wizard and is making bags of money, it seems, but something has gone wrong and she asked her mother to come visit her. Mart</span>
  <span id="freeText12088098526747436151" style="display:none">This is an absolute gem of a book!<br /><br />Odd, unconventional and uniformly charming to read it is rather unique and, as such, it is not easily boxed into any category, I would say that 'Fantasy', 'Classic science fiction', or 'magic realism' would all fit perfectly well.<br /><br />Martha Macnamara flies into town at the invitation of the daughter she has not seen for years. Liz is a computer wizard and is making bags of money, it seems, but something has gone wrong and she asked her mother to come visit her. Martha is an unconventional, middle aged musician who plays fiddle in a band, practices Zen, and lives so outside the box that she can bewilder passers by.<br /><br />Liz has organised for her to stay in a ritzy hotel, and on her first day there, she meets the intriguing Mayland Long, a Eurasian of extensive conversation and unusual stories. But the next thing that happens is that Liz vanishes and Mr Long offers to help Martha find her.<br /><br />That is the outline, and there is very little of fantasy in most of the story. Most of the time it is a straightforward, kidnapping/computer crime novel. The uniqueness and the fantasy creep in subtly and by insinuation. Most appropriate in a story that has a (hidden) dragon as a main character.<br /><br />The gentle charm is all in the writing and the outlook - and it grows on you! I have been re-reading this little book for years and am delighted anew at it every time.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12088098526747436151" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


